item.title: BATTLE OF THE ALAMO
item.description:
nflravens posted a photo:

The Battle of the Alamo (February 23 – March 6, 1836) was a pivotal event and military engagement in the Texas Revolution. Following a 13-day siege, Mexican troops under President General Antonio López de Santa Anna reclaimed the Alamo Mission near San Antonio de Béxar (now San Antonio). About one hundred Texians were garrisoned at the mission at the time, with around a hundred subsequent reinforcements led by eventual Alamo co-commanders James Bowie and William B. Travis.
www.billhunterphotography.com

item.title: MISSION CONCEPCION
item.description:
nflravens posted a photo:

Founded in 1716 in what is now eastern Texas, the mission was one of six authorized by the government to serve as a buffer against French incursions into Spanish territory from Louisiana.

Developed by Spanish Franciscan friars and after a tenuous existence and several moves, the mission was transferred to its present site in 1731.

item.title: MISSION ESPADA
item.description:
nflravens posted a photo:

Mission San Francisco de la Espada (also Mission Espada) is a Roman Rite Catholic mission established in 1690 by Spain and relocated in 1731 to present-day San Antonio, Texas, in what was then known as northern New Spain. The mission was built in order to convert local Native Americans to Christianity and solidify Spanish territorial claims in the New World against encroachment from France.
www.billhunterphotography.com

item.title: MISSION SAN JUAN
item.description:
nflravens posted a photo:

The history of Mission San Juan began in the woods of East Texas. In 1716, Mission San José de los Nazonis was established to serve the Nazonis Indians. However, the mission was not successful, and whatever was transportable was moved here. On March 5, 1731, the mission was reestablished on the east bank of the San Antonio River and renamed San Juan Capistrano.

item.title: SEAWORLD SAN ANTONIO
item.description:
nflravens posted a photo:

In March 2016, SeaWorld Entertainment announced that the current generation of orcas at its parks would be the last. SeaWorld San Antonio currently houses four orcas. It was also announced that the theatrical orca shows would be phased out and replaced with more naturalistic Orca Encounters.

item.title: SANTA ON HIS WAY
item.description:
nflravens posted a photo:

An architect named Robert H.H. Hugman proposed a plan to turn the area into a beautiful urban park with apartments, dining, shopping, boat rides, and walkways lit by old-fashioned street lamps. He wanted it to be just as if one were walking in Venice, Italy. After convincing city officials and business leaders of the financial benefits of his plan, the dream became a reality and the riverwalk was eventually sculpted into the masterpiece you see today.
